
[1]endure

   ENDU'RE, v.t. [L. durus, duro.]

   1. To last; to continue in the same state without perishing; to remain;
   to abide.

   The Lord shall endure forever. Ps.9.

   He shall hold it [his house] fast, but it shall not endure. Job.8.

   2. To bear; to brook; to suffer without resistance, or without
   yielding.

   How can I endure to see the evil that shall come to my people? Esther
   8.

   Can thy heart endure, or thy hands be strong? Ezek. 22.

      ENDU'RE, v.t. To bear; to sustain; to support without breaking or
    yielding to force or pressure. Metals endure a certain degree of heat
                              without melting.

   Both were of shining steel, and wrought so pure.

   As might the strokes of two such arms endure.

   1. To bear with patience; to bear without opposition or sinking under
   the pressure.

   Therefore, I endure all things for the elect's sake. 2 Tim 2.

   If ye endure chastening, God dealeth with you as with sons. Heb.12.

   2. To undergo; to sustain.

   I wish to die, yet dare not death endure.

   3. To continue in. [Not used.]
